3DB

	A networked database with a focus on vectorization built with Justine
	Tunney's cosmopolitan libc.

BUILDING

	% etc/cosmo.sh   # setup toolchain
	% make -j6       # build
	% make -j6 test  # run tests

CODEBASE REFERENCE

	=======================================================================
	| path           | description
	=----------------%-----------------------------------------------------
	| inc/u.h        | "Univeral" header. The "prelude".
	| inc/A.h        | A::A<X>: static width, memcpy-able vectors.
	| inc/Q.h        | Q::Q: bytecode VM stack object type.
	| inc/T.h        | T::T: an RC&COW database table object.
	| inc/Asm.h      | Asm::Asm: a serializable virtual machine object.
	| inc/cmd.h      | High-level C++ database command API.
	| inc/bc.h       | VM bytecode types, objects, and functions.
	| inc/sse.h      | SIMD SSE types and functions.
	| inc/mem.h      | Memory management functions.
	| inc/net.h      | Networking types and functions.
	| inc/net/*.h    | Send specific objects over the network.
	| inc/db.h       | Values and functions for managing the in-memory DB.
	| inc/fs.h       | Filesystem helpers.
	| inc/str.h      | Interned string table and other misc str functions.
	| inc/var.h      | var_t: variable name SSE representation.
	| inc/ini.h      | .ini config file parser.
	=----------------%-----------------------------------------------------
	| lib/bytes.cc   | Object serialization into raw buffers of bytes.
	| lib/Asm_exe.cc | Execute code inside an Asm::Asm.
	| lib/Cmd_exe.cc | Execute Cmd::Cmd commands. 
	| lib/fmt/*.cc   | Format objects into strings that you can print out.
	| lib/net/*.cc   | Send objects over the network.
	=======================================================================

RUNNING THE SERVER

	1. Make a config file cfg.ini (see example run/cfg.ini)
	2. zip -r o/3db/3db.com cfg.ini
	3. o/3db/3db.com

EXECUTING COMMANDS IN C++

	An example client program is included in this project under 3i (3
	interpreter). You can use this template to create your own query
	programs.

	A query is constructed through chains of methods. Note that these
	methods may throw runtime exceptions.

	=======================================================================
	| CREATE
	=======================================================================

	Create commands create entries in the database to be initialized later.

	/* create a table */
	auto cmd = Cmd::Cmd(Cmd::CREATE, "example.com:2222")
		.entry("table0")
		.type(Db::Tab)
		.columns({
			std::tuple{"int", T::TInt},
			std::tuple{"CHR", T::TCHR},
			std::tuple{"DBL", T::TDBL}
		});

	=======================================================================
	| INSERT
	=======================================================================

	Insert commands insert columns into tables in the database. This comm-
	and only works on tables.

	/* insert some stuff */
	auto cmd = Cmd::Cmd(Cmd::INSERT, "example.com:2222")
		.entry("table0")
		.row(22)
		.columns({
			Q::Q(1),
			Q::Q(A::A<Chr>{'a', 'b', 'c'}),
			Q::Q(A::A<f64>{1.2, 3.4, 5.6})
		});

	=======================================================================
	| SELECT
	=======================================================================

	Select commands select columns from tables entries. This command only
	works on tables.

	/* select a couple columns */
	auto cmd = Cmd::Cmd(Cmd::SELECT, 0)
		.entry("table1")
		.columns(A::A{"ints", "strs"});


